, is redeemed by a tradition of government intervention in economic and social life: the so-called "tory touch." This ground-breaking book begins with the now classic article in which the red tory view was formulated. It then presents a new and illuminating picture of Canadian political life, in which liberal individualism confronts not toryism but the participatory tradition of civic republicanism. In the final section the two editors, one a liberal, the other a civic republican, debate the crucial questions dominating Canadian politics today-including Quebec's search for recognition-from the perspective of their shared understanding of Canada's founding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh1 aAjzenstat, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Louis-Georges, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorowitz, Gad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnopff, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearce, Colin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVipond, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358042840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773580428423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773580428/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 